                     <unittitle>Taggart, Samuel (Washington, D.C.)</unittitle>
                  </did>
                  <odd id="aspace_993828819548aceb42a873efd601dbb2">
                     <head>General</head>
                     <p>Samuel Taggart (1754-1825) was a graduate of Dartmouth College who served as pastor of a church in Colrain, Mass. He was elected as a Federalist to the Eighth Congress and to six succeeding Congresses. He continued as pastor until Oct. 28, 1818. He died in Colrain April 25, 1825.</p>
                  </odd>
                  <c id="ref94" level="file">
                     <did>
                        <unittitle>1808 February 9</unittitle>
                        <unitdate unitdatetype="inclusive">1808 February 9</unitdate>
                        <container containerid="39002038200987"
                                   id="d1e596"
                                   label="Mixed Materials"
                                   localtype="box">1</container>
                        <container id="d1e598" localtype="folder" parent="d1e596">1</container>
                        <container id="d1e600" localtype="item" parent="d1e598">8</container>
                     </did>
                     <odd id="aspace_da519b96cda76043e4a1ba90cdd8aa04">
                        <head>General</head>
                        <p>This letter is concerned with Taggart's disenchantment with the nation's foreign policy, which he claims is influenced by powerful voices in Paris. He complains about the effects of the Embargo Act on American merchants and discusses the propriety of the British in regard to the Chesapeake incident and exaggerated charges of British
impressment of American sailors.</p>
                     </odd>
                  </c>
                  <c id="ref96" level="file">
                     <did>
                        <unittitle>1808 March 21</unittitle>
                        <unitdate unitdatetype="inclusive">1808 March 21</unitdate>
