               <c id="ref24" level="file">
                  <did>
                     <unittitle>Correspondence between Reverend Forward and Dr. Martin Phelps</unittitle>
                     <container containerid="39002038200987"
                                id="d1e725"
                                label="Mixed Materials"
                                localtype="box">1</container>
                     <container id="d1e727" localtype="folder" parent="d1e725">2</container>
                  </did>
                  <odd id="aspace_b3b11a88efdac6275597ef0c00e71594">
                     <head>General</head>
                     <p>Martin Phelps (1757-1838) was a graduate of Yale College, Class of 1776. After serving as physician and deacon in the Congregational Church in Haverhill, New Hampshire, he went to Belchertown. In 1796 his failure
to join the village church provoked notice. He was finally called on by the minister (Forward) and the deacons for his reasons. The two parties rushed into print and the letters between Phelps and Forward were published. By
the desire of the Reverend Aaron Bascom, the pastor of the church in Chester, Phelps removed thither. Soon a bitter controversy developed involving the entire community and Dr. Phelps was excommunicated from
the church. In 1807 he was chosen as an Anti-Federalist to represent the town in the state legislature. He subsequently renounced infant baptism and was admitted to the nearest Baptist church in Hinsdale. He was
instrumental in starting a Baptist society in Chester. He died there on Nov. 26, 1838.
This particular correspondence consists of four letters from Phelps to Forward and a copy of Forward's preface and his remarks to the public. The letters are concerned with Phelps' arguments behind his refusal to join the
church. The basic problem involves his interpretation of the qualities necessary for communion. Phelps claims that the church's practice is in opposition to the church's covenant. There has been no test to see if those receiving communion actually possess the essential characteristics of real Christians. Besides presenting his own arguments, Phelps refutes his opponent's reasons for church practice.</p>
                  </odd>
               </c>
